    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate leaning heavily into top-of-the-order firepower to drive our 5x5 production. **Trea Turner** (79.76) and **Kyle Schwarber** (78.41) serve as our clear offensive anchors, both benefiting from a soft matchup against Javier Assad (4.83 xERA). With favorable wind conditions and premium lineup spots, **Trea Turner** remains our highest-upside play, while **Kyle Schwarber**\u2019s elite xwOBA (0.402) provides the necessary power floor to mitigate the risk of a low-scoring game. Further down the order, **Josh Smith** (64.66) is an intriguing high-value start; his score is significantly inflated by an advantageous matchup against Luis Severino and favorable park factors, making him a superior play to several higher-drafted options today.\n\nWe are navigating a few tactical constraints in today\u2019s lineup construction. The most difficult bench decision involved **Carson Benge** (34.37), who failed to crack the starting nine due to a challenging matchup against Justin Wrobleski\u2019s sub-3.00 xERA. While **Carson Benge** offers versatility, the optimizer prioritized the volume and matchup potential of **Caleb Durbin** (65.73) and **Yordan Alvarez** (60.27). Risk management remains a priority; **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (42.94) is flirting with the below-floor threshold due to an unfavorable matchup against Cristopher S\u00e1nchez and a high-tier catcher\u2019s pop time hindering his elite stolen base potential. While we are currently deploying **Victor Scott II** (52.43) to chase the scarcity of SBs, owners should monitor the official lineup cards; should **Victor Scott II**, **Logan O'Hoppe**, or **Hyeseong Kim** be pushed down the batting order further than our \"Lineup Pending\" assumptions, their efficiency scores will drop immediately, potentially triggering mid-day swaps with the likes of **Colt Keith**, **Zac Veen**, or **Lars Nootbaar** if they are confirmed active. We are currently without the services of 